[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837784626775&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837784626775&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

&gt;nice if the root servers didn't have to deal with these bogus ".BITNET"
&gt;and ".SPAN" domains.  It is frightining at times watching a trace of
&gt;the TERP.UMD.EDU root name server to see how many queries it gets for
&gt;these two, and for another winner, the ever popular ".UUCP" domain.

The other possibility would be to MX .bitnet and .span -- and maybe
even .uucp -- to appropriate gateways.  There are a lot of sites that
define these domains locally.  The alternative is for our users to
have to keep track of where the best gateways are this week, and
remember the odd syntax for forwarding through them.  When we send
mail into the Internet we try to rewrite the headers so they are
legal, i.e. foo@bar.bitnet becomes foo%foo.bitnet@gateway or something
like that.  But our sendmail.cf maintainer is more ambitious than
most.  When the community as a whole supports domains that the root
servers refuse to acknowledge, there's going to be trouble in the long
run.

